<subSubSection pageId="0" pageNumber="1" type="remarks">
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="1">Remarks.</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="1">
The closest match for the COI sequence is a sequence from 
<taxonomicName genus="B." lsidName="B. sanguinolenta" pageId="0" pageNumber="1" rank="species" species="sanguinolenta">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="1">B. sanguinolenta</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
(GenBank: HM196505.1; 93.54% similarity) from the Ross Sea, Antarctica. A genetic study revealed two separate clades within 
<taxonomicName genus="B." lsidName="B. sanguinolenta" pageId="0" pageNumber="1" rank="species" species="sanguinolenta">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="1">B. sanguinolenta</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
(
<bibRefCitation DOI="https://doi.org/10.1016/j.dsr2.2010.10.011" author="O'Loughlin, PM" journalOrPublisher="Part II, Topical Studies in Oceanography" pageId="0" pageNumber="1" pagination="264 - 275" refId="B74" refString="O'Loughlin, PM, Paulay, G, Davey, N, Michonneau, F, 2011. The Antarctic region as a marine biodiversity hotspot for echinoderms: Diversity and diversification of sea cucumbers. Deep-sea Research. Part II, Topical Studies in Oceanography 58 (1-2): 264 - 275, DOI: https://doi.org/10.1016/j.dsr2.2010.10.011" title="The Antarctic region as a marine biodiversity hotspot for echinoderms: Diversity and diversification of sea cucumbers. Deep-sea Research." url="https://doi.org/10.1016/j.dsr2.2010.10.011" volume="58" year="2011">
<normalizedToken originalValue="O’Loughlin">O'Loughlin</normalizedToken>
et al. 2011
</bibRefCitation>
): (1) specimens from northwest Australia, and (2) Ross Sea. None of the samples included in 
<bibRefCitation DOI="https://doi.org/10.1016/j.dsr2.2010.10.011" author="O'Loughlin, PM" journalOrPublisher="Part II, Topical Studies in Oceanography" pageId="0" pageNumber="1" pagination="264 - 275" refId="B74" refString="O'Loughlin, PM, Paulay, G, Davey, N, Michonneau, F, 2011. The Antarctic region as a marine biodiversity hotspot for echinoderms: Diversity and diversification of sea cucumbers. Deep-sea Research. Part II, Topical Studies in Oceanography 58 (1-2): 264 - 275, DOI: https://doi.org/10.1016/j.dsr2.2010.10.011" title="The Antarctic region as a marine biodiversity hotspot for echinoderms: Diversity and diversification of sea cucumbers. Deep-sea Research." url="https://doi.org/10.1016/j.dsr2.2010.10.011" volume="58" year="2011">
<normalizedToken originalValue="O’Loughlin">O'Loughlin</normalizedToken>
et al. (2011)
</bibRefCitation>
are from the type locality (34.1167° S 73.9399°'W, off Chile, Pacific Ocean; 4000 m), but they identified at least two separate genetic species. The COI sequence of the specimen collected in the CCZ forms a third clade within the 
<taxonomicName genus="B." lsidName="B. sanguinolenta" pageId="0" pageNumber="1" rank="species" species="sanguinolenta">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="1">B. sanguinolenta</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
species complex (Fig. 
<figureCitation captionStart="Figure 34" captionStartId="F34" captionText="Figure 34. Phylogenetic tree of the class Holothuroidea. Concatenated (12 S, 16 S, 18 S, 28 S, COI, and H 3) median consensus BEAST tree with posterior probability (PP) and bootstrap (BS) values indicated. Only values of PP&gt; 0.70 and BS&gt; 50 are shown, with values of PP&gt; 0.95 and BS&gt; 90 indicated with a circle. Nodes not recovered on the RAxML tree are indicated with a hyphen. Sequences generated in this study are highlighted in violet." figureDoi="10.3897/zookeys.1113.82172.figure34" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/716360" pageId="0" pageNumber="1">34</figureCitation>
). Genetic divergence (K2P distance) between the CCZ specimens and both NW Australia and Ross Sea clades is 10.1% and 7.3%, respectively, corresponding to values of intraspecific divergence in the group. In original description, 
<bibRefCitation author="Theel, H" journalOrPublisher="Zoology (Jena, Germany)" pageId="0" pageNumber="1" pagination="1 - 176" refId="B95" refString="Theel, H, 1882. Report on the Holothuroidea dredged by H.M.S. 'Challenger' during the years 1873-76. Part i. Report on the scientific results of the voyage of H.M.S. Challenger during the years 1873-1876. Zoology (Jena, Germany) 4: 1 - 176" title="Report on the Holothuroidea dredged by H. M. S. ' Challenger' during the years 1873 - 76. Part i. Report on the scientific results of the voyage of H. M. S. Challenger during the years 1873 - 1876." volume="4" year="1882">
<normalizedToken originalValue="Théel">Theel</normalizedToken>
(1882)
</bibRefCitation>
describes the body to be 6-7 
<normalizedToken originalValue="×">x</normalizedToken>
longer than wide, whereas the preserved specimen collected in the CCZ is only ~ 3 
<normalizedToken originalValue="×">x</normalizedToken>
longer than wide, but might be due to preservation as in in situ images it appears longer. However, the number of digitiform tentacles and appearance of small processes are concordant with the description of 
<taxonomicName genus="B." lsidName="B. sanguinolenta" pageId="0" pageNumber="1" rank="species" species="sanguinolenta">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="1">B. sanguinolenta</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
. The sequence of 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Theel" authorityYear="1882" class="Ophiuroidea" family="Psychropotidae" genus="Benthodytes" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Benthodytes sanguinolenta" order="Elasipodida" pageId="0" pageNumber="1" phylum="Echinodermata" rank="species" species="sanguinolenta">Benthodytes cf. sanguinolenta</taxonomicName>
from 
<bibRefCitation DOI="https://doi.org/10.3897/BDJ.4.e7251" author="Glover, AG" journalOrPublisher="Journal of Marine Science and Engineering" pageId="0" pageNumber="1" refId="B33" refString="Glover, AG, Wiklund, H, Rabone, M, Amon, DJ, Smith, CR, O'Hara, T, Mah, CL, Dahlgren, TG, 2016b. Abyssal fauna of the UK-1 polymetallic nodule exploration claim, Clarion-Clipperton Zone, central Pacific Ocean: Echinodermata. Biodiversity Data Journal 4: e7251. https://doi.org/10.3897/BDJ.4.e7251" title="Abyssal fauna of the UK- 1 polymetallic nodule exploration claim, Clarion-Clipperton Zone, central Pacific Ocean: Echinodermata. Biodiversity Data Journal 4: e 7251." url="https://doi.org/10.3897/BDJ.4.e7251" year="2016 b">Glover et al. (2016b)</bibRefCitation>
does not form a clade with the CCZ specimen, with COI genetic distance being large (K2P 23%).
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="0" pageNumber="1" type="ecology">
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="1">Ecology.</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="1">The specimen was found on the sedimented seafloor of an abyssal plain in APEI 1 at 5249 m depth.</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="0" pageNumber="1" type="comparisons">
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="1">Comparison with image-based catalogue.</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="1">
No exactly similar 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Theel" authorityYear="1882" class="Ophiuroidea" family="Psychropotidae" genus="Benthodytes" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Benthodytes" order="Elasipodida" pageId="0" pageNumber="1" phylum="Echinodermata" rank="genus">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="1">Benthodytes</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
sp. morphotypes have been so far catalogued from seabed imagery collected in the eastern CCZ or in abyssal areas of the Kiribati EEZ. Consequently, the in situ image of specimen CCZ_178 was catalogued as a new morphotype (i.e., 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Theel" authorityYear="1882" class="Ophiuroidea" family="Psychropotidae" genus="Benthodytes" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Benthodytes sanguinolenta" order="Elasipodida" pageId="0" pageNumber="1" phylum="Echinodermata" rank="species" species="sanguinolenta">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="1">Benthodytes sanguinolenta</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
sp. inc., HOL_124).
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
